Review of ePDS-aq2.1 (da62854) found: the dark mode override for input placeholder color uses a hardcoded rgb value instead of the CSS custom property token system.

Evidence (login-page.ts lines 543-545):
  @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
    .input-field::placeholder { color: rgb(107 114 128); }
  }

This hardcodes a neutral gray (Tailwind gray-500) instead of using the purple-tinted token --color-text-light (which resolves to hsl(265 20% 71.8%) in dark mode). This breaks the consistency of the CSS token system that the rest of the component uses.

Fix: change to color: var(--color-text-light); (or remove the dark mode override entirely since the light mode rule already uses var(--color-text-light) which inverts correctly in dark mode via the contrast scale).

Review of ePDS-aq2.1 found: when initialStep='otp' and otpAlreadySent=false (first load with login_hint), the JS initialization block fires sendOtp(loginHint) asynchronously. The resend button (#btn-resend) is already visible and enabled at this point. If the user clicks 'Resend Code' before the auto-send fetch completes (~100-500ms), two concurrent sendOtp() calls go out, resulting in two OTP emails being sent.

Evidence (login-page.ts lines 975-984):
  if (!otpAlreadySent) {
    sendOtp(loginHint).then(function(result) { ... });  // async, doesn't disable resend
  }
The resend handler (lines 944-956) disables itself during its own call but has no awareness of the in-flight auto-send.

Fix: disable the resend button before the auto-send fires and re-enable it in the .then() callback:
  var resendBtn = document.getElementById('btn-resend');
  resendBtn.disabled = true;
  sendOtp(loginHint).then(function(result) {
    resendBtn.disabled = false;
    ...
  });

